= Project Summary/Abstract

As world proficiency with machine-learning models increases, interest in applying them to protein structure has grown as well. Multiple international research groups have already managed to use ML methods to accurately predict and produce proteins that do not exist in nature. However, producing a protein complex that can reliably perform a function (enzymes, hormones, catalysts) has proven to be difficult. Presently, it is possible to easily identify the stable state of a protein, but most actionable proteins have excited states that such models are unable to accurately predict. The long-term goal of this project is to develop a public Graph Neural model (GNN) that can accurately predict the ways in which activated proteins interact with their attached protein complexes, as well as the proteome at large. Furthermore, a clinically useful model must also account for tolerances to structural perturbation, identifying a threshold where significant structural deviation from normal flexibility results in a loss of function. Progression towards the goal of quantifiably useful custom proteins necessitates creating and improving ML methods capable of identifying non-equilibrium protein states. Many existing models may have an inherent "bias" that stems from authors focusing too much on a single version of a protein structure, leading to statistically impossible stability values inconsistent with nature within these models. The source of that bias may yet be circumvented by adjusting training to encompass protein subfamilies and superfamilies, along with conformational defects. These can then be incorporated by existing models to account for their internal stability bias. The first aim of this experiment is to investigate the validity of a transformer graph neural network (GNN) with an expanded variety of training datasets' ability to generalize across the broad kinase family. The second aim of this experiment is to investigate the transferability of a mutation load threshold across the kinase family. Point mutation load is used as an analog for the statistical probability of miniscule damage or misfolding that overall does not affect protein function. I expect to see that across the broad family of kinases the relevant structural change to be similar and for the model to be an effective predictor, but individual factors must be investigated as well. Similarly, I expect there will be a common mutation threshold of protein damage linking to nonfunction. The impact of this study has the potential to be a first step towards widespread innovation in many sectors. With an accurate GNN, it would become possible to reorient existing methods, leading to a boom in the medical field. Cellular delivery vectors, vaccines, treatments for autoimmune disorders, and custom anti-bodies are all possible novel breakthroughs.
